  "prompt": "What is the difference between overhanging beam and cantilever beam?",
  "response": "The terms **overhanging beam** and **cantilever beam** are both used in structural engineering to describe types of beams, but they have distinct characteristics and applications:\n\n### 1. **Cantilever Beam**:\n   - A cantilever beam is a type of beam that is supported at only one end, with the other end free (unsupported).\n   - **Key Features**:\n     - Fixed at one end (support can be a wall, column, or another beam).\n     - The other end extends freely without any support.\n     - The fixed end resists both bending moments and shear forces.\n   - **Applications**:\n     - Balconies, diving boards, cantilevered roofs, and aircraft wings.\n   - **Behavior**:\n     - It experiences significant bending stress and deflection at the free end.\n\n### 2. **Overhanging Beam**:\n   - An overhanging beam is a beam that extends beyond one or both of its supports.\n   - **Key Features**:\n     - The beam has at least one support at one end and extends beyond another support.\n     - The overhanging portion is not supported and can experience bending and shear forces.\n   - **Applications**:\n     - Bridge decks, shelf supports, and structural elements where a beam needs to extend beyond its supports.\n   - **Behavior**:\n     - The overhanging portion behaves like a cantilever, but the presence of the additional support(s) modifies the internal forces and deflections.\n\n### **Key Differences**:\n\n| Feature                | **Cantilever Beam**                    | **Overhanging Beam**                     |\n|------------------------|----------------------------------------|------------------------------------------|\n| **Supports**           | Supported at only one end              | Supported at one or both ends, with an unsupported overhang |\n| **Free End**           | One end is entirely free               | One or both ends extend beyond the support(s) |\n| **Behavior**           | Acts like a single cantilever          | Combines simply supported and cantilever behavior |\n| **Applications**       | Balconies, diving boards               | Bridges, shelves, extended structures    |\n\n### Summary:\n- A **cantilever beam** is supported at only one end and is free at the other end.\n- An **overhanging beam** has supports at one or both ends but extends beyond one or more of those supports.\n\nBoth types of beams experience bending moments and shear forces, but their support conditions and applications differ.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
